Do you want to be the next Director of Public Prosecutions (DPP)? Well, you have six days to apply. The position was advertised in the State-run MyGov on Tuesday. ALSO READ:

Court orders IG Boinnet, DCI to produce Miguna by 2pm Candidates should submit their applications to the Public Service Commission. The recruitment panel, led by Dr Elizabeth Muli, said Keriako Tobiko's successor should have served as a judge of a superior court or magistrate for at least 10 years, or be a distinguished legal practitioner or academician with at least 10 years' experience. Women, minorities, the marginalised, and the disabled were encouraged to apply.